ion’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705189,"age":9,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705190,"age":40,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When William Wyncelowe was born in 1250, in London, Middlesex, England, his father, Enos Wyncelowe, was 65 and his mother, Agnes I. Arden, was 65. He had at least 1 son with Margeria Chasteleyne. He died in 1298, in his hometown, at the age of 48, and was buried in London, Middlesex, England."},"et":{"1250–1298":"1250–1298","1250–Female":"1250–Surnud","1274–1365":"1274–1365","1185–Male":"1185–Surnud","1185–Female":"1185–Surnud","Abt 1274":"umbes 1274","1259":"1259","1365":"1365","1298":"1298","1274":"1274","1185":"1185","1250":"1250","1290":"1290","London, Middlesex, England":"London, Middlesex, England"},"fi":{"1250–1298":"1250–1298","1250–Female":"1250–Kuollut","1274–1365":"1274–1365","1185–Male":"1185–Kuollut","1185–Female":"1185–Kuollut","Abt 1274":"noin 1274","1259":"1259","1365":"1365","1298":"1298","1274":"1274","1185":"1185","1250":"1250","1290":"1290","London, Middlesex, England":"London, Middlesex, England"},"fr":{"1250–1